WEBVTT

00:24.700 --> 00:29.480
II. WHERE I LIVED, AND WHAT

00:29.480 --> 00:30.560
I LIVED FOR

00:32.940 --> 00:39.200
At a certain season of our lives we are accustomed to consider every spot as the possible site

00:39.200 --> 00:44.880
of a house. I have thus surveyed the country on every side within a dozen miles of where

00:44.880 --> 00:52.180
I live. In imagination I have bought all the farms in succession, for all were to be bought,

00:52.180 --> 00:59.720
and I knew their price. I walked over each farmer's premises, tasted his wild apples,

01:00.400 --> 01:06.580
discoursed on husbandry with him, took his farm at his price, at any price, mortgaging

01:06.580 --> 01:14.280
it to him in my mind, even put a higher price on it, took everything but a deed of it, took

01:14.280 --> 01:21.380
his word for his deed, for I dearly loved to talk, cultivated it, and him too to some

01:21.380 --> 01:28.280
extent, I trust, and withdrew when I had enjoyed it long enough, leaving him to carry it on.

01:29.300 --> 01:36.140
This experience entitled me to be regarded as a sort of real estate broker by my friends.

01:37.700 --> 01:44.120
Wherever I sat there I might live, and the landscape radiated from me accordingly.

01:45.880 --> 01:56.240
What is a house, but a sedge, a seat? Better if a country seat. I discovered many a site

01:56.240 --> 02:01.420
for a house not likely to be soon improved, which some might have thought too far from

02:01.420 --> 02:06.340
the village, but to my eyes the village was too far from it.

02:07.280 --> 02:15.380
Well, there I might live, I said, and there I did live, for an hour, a summer, and a winter

02:15.380 --> 02:23.900
life, saw how I could let the years run off, buffet the winter through, and see the spring

02:23.900 --> 02:31.000
come in. The future inhabitants of this region, wherever they may place their houses, may

02:31.000 --> 02:37.700
be sure that they have been anticipated. An afternoon sufficed to lay out the land

02:37.700 --> 02:45.360
into orchard, wood lot, and pasture, and to decide what fine oaks or pines should be left

02:45.360 --> 02:51.840
to stand before the door, and whence each blasted tree could be seen to the best advantage.

02:53.060 --> 03:00.980
And then I let it lie, fallow, perchance, for a man is rich in proportion to the number

03:00.980 --> 03:08.820
of things which he can afford to let alone. My imagination carried me so far that I even

03:08.820 --> 03:16.580
had the refusal of several farms. The refusal was all I wanted, but I never got my fingers

03:16.580 --> 03:24.860
burned by actual possession. The nearest that I came to actual possession was when I bought

03:24.860 --> 03:31.560
the hollow-well place, and had begun to sort my seeds, and collected materials with which

03:31.560 --> 03:37.880
to make a wheel-barrow to carry it on or off with. But before the owner gave me a deed

03:37.880 --> 03:46.160
of it, his wife, every man has such a wife, changed her mind, and wished to keep it, and

03:46.160 --> 03:53.200
he offered me ten dollars to release him. Now, to speak the truth, I had but ten cents

03:53.200 --> 03:59.780
in the world, and it surpassed my arithmetic to tell if I was that man who had ten cents,

03:59.880 --> 04:07.940
or who had a farm, or ten dollars, or altogether. However, I let him keep the ten dollars and

04:07.940 --> 04:15.340
the farm too, for I had carried it far enough. Or rather, to be generous, I sold him the

04:15.340 --> 04:21.860
farm for just what I gave for it, and, as he was not a rich man, made him a present

04:21.860 --> 04:27.880
of ten dollars, and still had my ten cents, and seeds, and materials for a wheel-barrow

04:27.880 --> 04:37.200
left. I found thus that I had been a rich man without any damage to my poverty, but

04:37.200 --> 04:43.780
I retained the landscape, and I have since annually carried off what it yielded without

04:43.780 --> 04:51.840
a wheel-barrow. With respect to landscapes, quote, I am monarch of the world, and of

04:51.860 --> 04:58.920
all I survey, my right there is none to dispute. End quote.

05:00.120 --> 05:07.040
I have frequently seen a poet withdraw, having enjoyed the most valuable part of a farm,

05:07.700 --> 05:14.880
while the crusty farmer supposed that he had got a few wild apples only. Why, the owner

05:14.880 --> 05:21.780
does not know it, for many years, when a poet has put his farm in rhyme, the most admirable

05:21.780 --> 05:29.920
kind of invisible fence, has fairly impounded it, milked it, skimmed it, and got all the

05:29.920 --> 05:33.200
cream, and left the farmer only the skimmed milk.

05:34.180 --> 05:41.900
The real attractions of the Hollow Well farm to me were its complete retirement, being

05:41.900 --> 05:47.580
about two miles from the village, half a mile from the nearest neighbor, and separated from

05:47.580 --> 05:53.940
the highway by a broad field. Its bounding on the river, which the owner said protected

05:53.940 --> 06:02.160
it, by its fogs from frosts in the spring, though that was nothing to me. The gray color

06:02.160 --> 06:09.220
and ruinous state of the house and barn, and the dilapidated fences, which put such an

06:09.220 --> 06:16.320
interval between me and the last occupant. The hollow and lichen-covered apple trees,

06:16.320 --> 06:24.240
gnawed by rabbits, showing what kind of neighbors I should have. But above all, the recollection

06:24.240 --> 06:30.700
I had of it from my earliest voyages up the river, when the house was concealed behind

06:30.700 --> 06:38.980
a dense grove of red maples, through which I heard the house-dog bark. I was in haste

06:38.980 --> 06:44.080
to buy it, before the proprietor finished getting out some rocks, cutting down the hollow

06:44.080 --> 06:50.480
apple trees, and grubbing up some young birches which had sprung up in the pasture, or in

06:50.480 --> 06:58.220
short had made any more of his improvements. To enjoy these advantages I was ready to carry

06:58.220 --> 07:06.920
it on, like Atlas to take the world on my shoulders. I never heard what compensation he received

07:06.920 --> 07:13.900
for that. And to all those things which had no other motive or excuse but that I might

07:13.900 --> 07:20.580
pay for it and be unmolested in my possession of it, for I knew all the while that it would

07:20.580 --> 07:27.220
yield the most abundant crop of the kind I wanted, if I could only afford to let it

07:27.220 --> 07:34.480
alone. But it turned out as I have said. All that I could say then, with respect to farming

07:34.480 --> 07:42.460
on a large scale—I have always cultivated a garden—was that I had my seeds ready.

07:43.900 --> 07:49.600
Many think that seeds improve with age. I have no doubt that time discriminates between

07:49.600 --> 07:55.180
the good and the bad, and when at last I shall plant I shall be less likely to be disappointed.

07:56.880 --> 08:05.040
But I would say to my fellows, once for all, as long as possible, live free and uncommitted.

08:06.000 --> 08:10.880
It makes but little difference whether you are committed to a farm or the county jail.

08:11.900 --> 08:22.760
Old Cato, whose direrustica is my cultivator, says, and the only translation I have seen

08:22.760 --> 08:29.640
makes sheer nonsense of the passage, quote, When you think of getting a farm, turn it

08:29.640 --> 08:37.320
thus in your mind, not to buy greedily, nor spare your pains to look at it, and do not

08:37.320 --> 08:44.200
think it enough to go round it once. The oftener you go there, the more it will please you,

08:44.340 --> 08:54.180
if it is good. I think I shall not buy greedily, but go round and round it, as long as I live,

08:54.980 --> 08:59.440
and be buried in it first, that it may please me the more at last.

09:00.620 --> 09:05.720
The present was my next experiment of this kind, which I purposed to describe more at

09:05.720 --> 09:13.040
length, for convenience putting the experience of two years into one. As I have said, I do

09:13.040 --> 09:20.480
not propose to write an ode to dejection, but to brag as lustily as Chanticleer in the

09:20.480 --> 09:27.440
morning standing on his roost, if only to wake my neighbors up. When first I took up

09:27.440 --> 09:33.520
my abode in the woods, that is, began to spend my nights as well as my days there, which

09:33.520 --> 09:41.820
by accident was on Independence Day, or the Fourth of July, 1845. My house was not finished

09:41.820 --> 09:49.160
for winter, but was merely a defense against the rain, without plastering or chimney, the

09:49.160 --> 09:55.460
walls being of rough weather-stained boards with wide chinks which made it cool at night.

09:56.480 --> 10:04.140
The upright white hewn studs and freshly plain door and window casings gave it a clean and

10:04.140 --> 10:10.220
airy look, especially in the morning when its timbers were saturated with dew, so that

10:10.220 --> 10:18.200
I fancied that by noon some sweet gum would exude from them. To my imagination it retained

10:18.200 --> 10:24.400
throughout the day more or less of this auroral character, reminding me of a certain house

10:24.400 --> 10:31.660
on a mountain which I had visited a year before. This was an airy and unplastered cabin

10:31.660 --> 10:39.800
fit to entertain a traveling god, and where a goddess might trail her garments. The winds

10:39.800 --> 10:46.280
which passed over my dwelling were such as sweep over the ridges of mountains, bearing

10:46.280 --> 10:54.380
the broken strains, or celestial parts only, of terrestrial music. The morning came to

10:54.400 --> 11:04.140
bring wind forever blows. The poem of creation is uninterrupted, but few are the ears that

11:04.140 --> 11:11.280
hear it. Olympus is but the outside of the earth everywhere.

11:12.540 --> 11:20.320
The only house I had been the owner of before, if I accept a boat, was a tent, which I used

11:20.320 --> 11:24.820
occasionally when making excursions in the summer, and this is still rolled up in my

11:24.820 --> 11:31.940
garret. But the boat, after passing from hand to hand, has gone down the stream of time.

11:32.960 --> 11:39.540
With this more substantial shelter about me, I had made some progress toward settling in

11:39.540 --> 11:50.300
the world. This frame, so slightly clad, was a sort of crystallization around for me.

11:53.820 --> 12:02.720
It was suggestive somewhat, as a picture in outlines. I did not need to go outdoors

12:02.720 --> 12:09.100
to take the air, for the atmosphere within had lost none of its freshness. It was not

12:09.100 --> 12:18.660
so much within doors as behind a door where I sat, even in the rainiest weather. The Haravansa

12:18.660 --> 12:29.880
says, An abode without birds is like a meat without seasoning. Such was not my abode,

12:30.100 --> 12:38.080
for I found myself suddenly neighbor to the birds, not by having imprisoned one, but having

12:38.080 --> 12:45.120
caged myself near them. I was not only nearer to some of those which commonly frequent the

12:45.120 --> 12:54.440
orchard, but to those smaller and more thrilling songsters of the forest, which never or rarely

12:54.440 --> 13:03.360
serenade a villager, the wood thrush, the veerie, the scarlet tannanger, the field sparrow,

13:03.640 --> 13:06.140
the whippoorwill, and many others.

13:07.720 --> 13:14.060
I was seated by the shore of a small pond, about a mile and a half south of the village

13:14.060 --> 13:19.720
of Concord, and somewhat higher than it, in the midst of an extensive wood between

13:19.720 --> 13:26.560
that town and Lincoln, and about two miles south of that our only field known to fame,

13:27.060 --> 13:33.480
Concord Battleground. But I was so low in the woods that the opposite shore, half a

13:33.480 --> 13:39.200
mile off, like the rest, covered with wood, was my most distant horizon.

13:40.680 --> 13:48.640
For the first week, whenever I looked out on the pond, it impressed me like a tarn high

13:48.640 --> 13:55.500
up on the side of a mountain, its bottom far above the surface of other lakes, and as the

13:55.500 --> 14:02.920
sun arose I saw it throwing off its nightly clothing of mist, and here and there by degrees

14:03.340 --> 14:11.660
its soft ripples where its smooth reflecting surface was revealed, while the mists, like

14:11.660 --> 14:19.000
ghosts, were stealthily withdrawing in every direction into the woods, as at the breaking

14:19.000 --> 14:28.440
up of some nocturnal conventicle. The very dew seemed to hang upon the trees later into

14:28.440 --> 14:37.320
the day than usual, as on the sides of mountains. This small lake was of most value as a neighbor

14:37.320 --> 14:44.340
in the intervals of a gentle rainstorm in August, when, both air and water being perfectly

14:44.340 --> 14:53.040
still but the sky overcast, mid-afternoon had all the serenity of evening, and the wood

14:53.040 --> 15:02.760
brush sang around and was heard from shore to shore. A lake like this is never smoother

15:02.760 --> 15:12.560
than at such a time, and the clear portion of the air above it, being shallow and darkened

15:12.560 --> 15:23.020
by clouds, the water full of light and reflections, becomes a lower heaven itself so far above

15:23.040 --> 15:32.760
so much the more important. From a hilltop nearby, where the wood had been recently cut

15:32.760 --> 15:40.080
off, there was a pleasing vista southward across the pond, through a wide indentation

15:40.080 --> 15:46.620
in the hills which formed the shore there, where their opposite sides sloping toward

15:46.620 --> 15:52.260
each other suggested a stream flowing out in that direction, through a wooded valley,

15:52.940 --> 16:00.780
but stream there was none. That way I looked between and over the near green hills to some

16:00.780 --> 16:09.920
distant and higher ones in the horizon, tinged with blue. Indeed, by standing on tiptoe,

16:10.020 --> 16:15.440
I could catch a glimpse of some of the peaks of the still bluer and more distant mountain

16:15.440 --> 16:24.080
ranges in the northwest, those true blue coins from heaven's own mint, and also of some portion

16:24.080 --> 16:31.880
of the village. But in other directions, even from this point, I could not see over or beyond

16:31.880 --> 16:39.340
the woods which surrounded me. It is well to have some water in your neighborhood, to

16:39.340 --> 16:48.200
give buoyancy to and float the earth. One value even of the smallest well is that when

16:48.200 --> 16:58.600
you look into it you see that earth is not continent, but insular. This is as important

16:58.600 --> 17:05.500
as that it keeps butter cool. When I looked across the pond from this peak toward the

17:05.500 --> 17:11.180
Sudbury Meadows, which in time of flood I distinguished elevated perhaps by a mirage

17:11.180 --> 17:18.170
in their seething valley, like a coin in a basin, all the earth beyond the pond appeared

17:18.840 --> 17:27.840
like a thin crust insulated and floated even by this small sheet of interverting water,

17:28.430 --> 17:34.900
and I was reminded that this on which I dwelt was but dry land.

17:36.180 --> 17:42.280
Though the view from my door was still more contracted, I did not feel crowded or confined

17:42.280 --> 17:50.960
in the least. There was pasture enough for my imagination. The low shrub oak plateau,

17:51.440 --> 17:57.540
to which the opposite shore arose, stretched away toward the prairies of the west, and

17:57.540 --> 18:06.240
the steppes of tartary, affording ample room for all the roving families of men. There

18:06.240 --> 18:16.280
are none happy in the world but beings who enjoy freely a vast horizon, said Damodara

18:16.640 --> 18:25.340
when his herds required new and larger pastures. Both place and time were changed, and I dwelt

18:25.340 --> 18:31.620
nearer to those parts of the universe and to those eras in history which had most attracted

18:31.620 --> 18:41.240
me. Where I lived was as far off as many a region viewed nightly by astronomers. We are

18:41.240 --> 18:48.880
wont to imagine rare and delectable places in some remote and more celestial corner of

18:48.880 --> 18:58.940
the system. Behind the constellation of Cassiopeia's chair, far from noise and disturbance, I discovered

18:58.940 --> 19:08.560
that my house actually had its sight in such a withdrawn but forever new and unprofaned

19:08.560 --> 19:15.840
part of the universe. If it were worth the while to settle in those parts near to the

19:15.840 --> 19:25.300
Hyades, or the Hyades, or to Aldebaran or Altair, then I was really there, or at an

19:25.300 --> 19:31.620
equal remoteness from the life which I had left behind, dwindled and twinkling, with

19:31.620 --> 19:38.960
his fine array to my nearest neighbor, and to be seen only in moonless nights by him.

19:39.850 --> 19:48.540
Such was that part of creation where I had squatted. There was a shepherd that did live

19:48.540 --> 19:55.840
and held his thoughts as high as were the mounts whereon his flocks did hourly feed

19:55.840 --> 20:05.720
him by. What should we think of the shepherd's life if his flocks always wandered to higher

20:05.720 --> 20:13.040
pastures than his thoughts? Every morning was a cheerful invitation to make my life

20:13.040 --> 20:22.660
of equal simplicity, and I may say innocence, with nature herself. I have been as sincere

20:22.660 --> 20:35.700
a worshiper of Aurora as the Greeks. I got up early and bathed in the pond. That was

20:35.700 --> 20:42.280
what they say, that characters were engraven on the bathing tub of King Chingthang to

20:42.280 --> 20:52.900
this effect, quote, Renew thyself completely each day. Do it again and again and forever

20:52.900 --> 21:05.680
again, end quote. I can understand that. Mourning brings back the heroic ages. I was ever a

21:05.700 --> 21:12.660
as much affected by the faint hum of a mosquito making its invisible and unimaginable tour

21:12.660 --> 21:18.500
through my apartment at earliest dawn, when I was sitting with door and windows open,

21:18.920 --> 21:28.400
as I could be by any trumpet that ever sang of fame. It was Homer's Requiem, itself an

21:28.400 --> 21:37.420
Iliad and Odyssey in the air, singing its own wrath and wanderings. There was something

21:37.420 --> 21:46.840
cosmical about it, a standing advertisement, till forbidden, of the everlasting vigor and

21:46.840 --> 21:55.960
fertility of the world. The morning, which is the most memorable season of the day, is

21:55.960 --> 22:07.060
the awakening hour. Then there is least somnolence in us, and for an hour at least some part

22:07.060 --> 22:15.420
of us awakes, which slumbers all the rest of the day and night. Little is to be expected

22:15.420 --> 22:23.780
of that day, if it can be called a day to which we are not awakened by our genius, but

22:23.780 --> 22:32.420
by the mechanical nudgings of some servitor, are not awakened by our own newly acquired

22:32.420 --> 22:41.620
force and aspirations from within, accompanied by the undulations of celestial music instead

22:41.620 --> 22:49.060
of factory bells and a fragrance filling the air, to a higher life than we fell asleep

22:49.060 --> 22:57.720
from. And thus the darkness bear its fruit and prove itself to be good, no less than

22:57.720 --> 23:07.760
the light. That man who does not believe that each day contains an earlier, more sacred

23:07.760 --> 23:17.920
and auroral hour than he has yet profaned, has despaired of life, and is pursuing a descending

23:17.920 --> 23:27.640
and darkening way. After a partial cessation of his sensuous life, the soul of man, or

23:27.640 --> 23:36.600
its organs rather, are reinvigorated each day and his genius tries again what noble

23:36.600 --> 23:44.800
life it can make. All memorable events, I should say, transpire in morning time and

23:44.800 --> 23:57.180
in a morning atmosphere. The Vedas say, all intelligences awake with the morning. Poetry

23:57.180 --> 24:04.280
and art and the fairest and most memorable of the actions of men date from such an hour.

24:05.420 --> 24:14.060
All poets and heroes like Memnon are the children of Aurora and emit their music at sunrise.

24:15.420 --> 24:23.680
To him whose elastic and vigorous thought keeps pace with the sun, the day is a perpetual

24:23.680 --> 24:32.140
morning. It matters not what the clocks say or the attitudes and labours of men. Morning

24:32.620 --> 24:43.300
is when I am awake and there is a dawn in me. Moral reform is the effort to throw off

24:43.300 --> 24:52.280
sleep. Why is it that men give so poor an account of their day if they have not been

24:52.280 --> 25:00.560
slumbering? They are not such poor calculators. If they had not been overcome with drowsiness

25:00.560 --> 25:11.000
they would have performed something. The millions are awake enough for physical labour, but

25:11.000 --> 25:22.060
only one in a million is awake enough for effective intellectual exertion, only one

25:22.060 --> 25:34.420
in a hundred millions to a poetic or divine life. To be awake is to be alive. I have never

25:34.420 --> 25:45.160
yet met a man who was quite awake. How could I have looked him in the face? We must learn

25:45.160 --> 25:54.320
to reawaken and keep ourselves awake, not by mechanical aids but by an infinite expectation

25:54.320 --> 26:03.080
of the dawn, which does not forsake us in our soundest sleep. I know of no more encouraging

26:03.080 --> 26:11.160
fact than the unquestionable ability of man to elevate his life by a conscious endeavour.

26:12.020 --> 26:18.940
It is something to be able to paint a particular picture or to carve a statue, and so to make

26:18.940 --> 26:29.580
a few objects beautiful. But it is far more glorious to carve and paint the very atmosphere

26:29.580 --> 26:39.660
and medium through which we look, which morally we can do. To affect the quality of the day,

26:39.960 --> 26:50.740
that is the highest of arts. Every man is tasked to make his life, even in its details,

26:51.320 --> 26:59.560
worthy of the contemplation of his most elevated and critical hour. If we refused, we would

26:59.580 --> 27:07.240
or rather used up such paltry information as we get, the oracles would distinctly inform

27:07.240 --> 27:09.420
us how this might be done.

